      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the choux and bake, 25 to 30 minutes",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 200°C fan. Put the {{unsalted-butter}} (pastry amount), {{sea-salt-fine}}, and 240 ml cold water in a saucepan. Heat until the butter melts and the water comes to a rolling boil. Remove from the heat, tip in the {{plain-flour}} all at once, and beat hard with a wooden spoon until the mixture pulls away from the sides and forms a ball. Return to the heat for 1 minute to dry out slightly. Transfer to a bowl and cool for 5 minutes. Beat in the {{eggs}} a little at a time until the paste is glossy and falls reluctantly from the spoon. Pipe walnut-sized mounds onto lined baking trays, spacing 4 cm apart. Bake for 25 to 30 minutes, until deep gold. Pierce each puff immediately. Return to the switched-off oven for 3 minutes. Cool on a rack.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fill and sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whip the {{double-cream}} (filling amount) with the {{icing-sugar}} and {{vanilla-extract}} to soft peaks. Split each puff and fill with cream, or pipe through the base. For the sauce, heat the {{double-cream}} (sauce amount) until steaming. Pour over the {{dark-chocolate}} and leave 30 seconds, then stir smooth. Stir in the {{unsalted-butter}} (sauce amount). Pile the profiteroles and pour the warm sauce over at the table.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
